  "prompt": "Which is the best book of linear algebra?",
  "response": "The \"best\" book on linear algebra can vary depending on your background, interests, and what you are looking to achieve. However, here are some highly regarded books on the subject:\n\n1. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - This book is praised for its clear exposition and focus on concepts rather than computational techniques. It's particularly well-suited for those who have some mathematical maturity and are looking to understand the theory behind linear algebra.\n\n2. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang** - Strang's book is known for its applications and clarity. It's widely used in undergraduate courses and provides a good balance between theory and practice.\n\n3. **\"Linear Algebra\" by Georgi E. Shilov** - This book offers a solid theoretical approach to the subject and is part of the Dover Books on Mathematics series, known for their affordability and quality.\n\n4. **\"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by David C. Lay, Steven R. Lay, and Judi J. McDonald** - This book is often used in university courses and covers a wide range of applications, making it very practical for engineering and computer science students.\n\n5. **\"Linear Algebra\" by Serge Lang** - This text offers a thorough and rigorous introduction to the subject and is often recommended for mathematics majors.\n\n6. **\"Finite-Dimensional Vector Spaces\" by Paul R. Halmos** - A classic in the field, this book provides a deep understanding of linear algebra and its connections with other areas of mathematics.\n\nEach of these books has its strengths, so the choice may depend on your particular needs, such as whether you are seeking a practical approach or a more theoretical one.",
